(47, 3, 5, 50, 2, 13, 13, 'our sufficiency is of God', 'Divine Sufficiency and Action', 'Both passages emphasize that our abilities and actions are derived from God. 2 Corinthians highlights our sufficiency as coming from God, while Philippians states that God works in us to fulfill His purposes.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 5, 43, 15, 5, 5, 'our sufficiency is of God', 'Sufficiency in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of divine support for human effectiveness. 2 Corinthians highlights that our sufficiency is from God, while John states that without Christ, we can do nothing.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 5, 59, 1, 17, 17, 'sufficiency is of God', 'Divine Sufficiency and Gifts', 'This connection highlights the source of sufficiency and gifts as coming from God. Both passages emphasize that all good and perfect gifts, as well as our sufficiency, originate from God.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 5, 40, 10, 19, 20, 'our sufficiency is of God', 'Divine Sufficiency in Speech', 'Both passages emphasize reliance on God for communication. 2 Corinthians highlights that our sufficiency is from God, while Matthew assures that the Spirit will provide the words to speak.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 6, 43, 6, 63, 63, 'the spirit giveth life', 'Connection of Spirit and Life', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the spirit in giving life. In 2 Corinthians, the spirit is contrasted with the letter, which kills, while in John, the spirit quickens and the flesh profits nothing.', 'theme', 0.524, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 6, 45, 7, 6, 6, NULL, 'Newness of Spirit vs. Old Letter', 'Both passages emphasize serving in ''newness of spirit'' rather than the ''oldness of the letter.'' This connection highlights the contrast between the life-giving spirit and the deathly letter of the law.', 'theme', 0.51, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 6, 24, 31, 31, 31, 'new testament', 'Connection of New Testament and Covenant', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a ''new'' covenant or testament. 2 Corinthians speaks of ministers of the ''new testament,'' while Jeremiah prophesies a ''new covenant'' with Israel and Judah.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 6, 45, 8, 2, 2, 'the spirit giveth life', 'Spirit and Life Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the spirit in granting life and freedom. The ''spirit'' in 2 Corinthians 3:6 contrasts with the ''law'' that brings death, while Romans 8:2 speaks of the ''law of the Spirit of life'' that liberates from sin and death.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 6, 58, 8, 6, 10, 'new testament', 'Connection of New Covenant Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a ''new covenant'' and the transition from the old to the new. 2 Corinthians highlights the difference between the letter and the spirit, while Hebrews elaborates on the establishment of a better covenant with internalized laws.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 6, 46, 15, 45, 45, 'the spirit giveth life', 'Spirit and Life Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between the life-giving spirit and the limitations of the flesh. The ''quickening spirit'' in 1 Corinthians reflects the ''spirit'' that ''giveth life'' in 2 Corinthians, highlighting the transformative power of the new covenant.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 6, 47, 3, 14, 14, 'the spirit giveth life', 'Connection of Spirit and Vail', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between the old and new testament, highlighting how the ''letter'' leads to blindness while the ''spirit'' brings life. The vail mentioned in the second passage signifies the barrier to understanding that is removed in Christ, aligning with the theme of spiritual enlightenment in the first passage.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 7, 47, 3, 9, 11, 'ministration of death', 'Glory of Ministry Comparison', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between the glory of the old covenant, described as ''ministration of death,'' and the surpassing glory of the new covenant, termed ''ministration of righteousness.'' This connection highlights how the glory of the old is ultimately diminished in light of the greater glory that remains.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 7, 2, 31, 18, 18, NULL, 'Glory of the Law', 'This connection highlights the significance of the ''tables of stone'' in both passages, emphasizing the glory associated with the Law given to Moses. The ''ministration of death'' in 2 Corinthians refers to the same tablets that were ''written and engraven in stones'' in Exodus.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 7, 45, 10, 4, 4, 'which glory was to be done away', 'Glory and the End of Law', 'This connection highlights the transition from the glory associated with the law, as seen in Moses'' countenance, to the fulfillment of that law in Christ. Both passages emphasize the shift from the old covenant, which was glorious yet temporary, to the new covenant established through faith in Christ.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 7, 46, 13, 10, 10, 'which glory was to be done away', 'Glory and Completion in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the transition from the glory of the old covenant, which was temporary, to the arrival of the perfect, which signifies a complete revelation. Both passages emphasize the idea of something glorious being done away with as a new, perfect reality emerges.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 7, 47, 3, 3, 3, NULL, 'Contrast of Ministry Types', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the ''ministration of death'' in 2 Corinthians 3:7 and the ''epistle of Christ'' in 3:3. Both passages emphasize the difference between the old covenant, represented by stone, and the new covenant, written on the heart.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 7, 2, 24, 12, 12, 'written and engraven in stones', 'Glory of the Law', 'This connection highlights the glory associated with the law given to Moses, as seen in both passages. 2 Corinthians 3:7 refers to the ''ministration of death, written and engraven in stones,'' which directly relates to the ''tables of stone'' mentioned in Exodus 24:12.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 7, 5, 10, 1, 4, 'written and engraven in stones', 'Glory of the Law', 'This connection highlights the glory associated with the law given on stone tablets. Both passages emphasize the significance of the commandments inscribed on stone, reflecting the divine authority and glory that accompanied their delivery.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 3, 8, 46, 3, 16, 16, 'ministration of the spirit', 'Connection of Spirit and Glory', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Spirit in believers. The ''ministration of the spirit'' in 2 Corinthians highlights the glory associated with the Spirit, while 1 Corinthians identifies believers as the ''temple of God'' where the Spirit dwells, suggesting a shared theme of divine presence and glory.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
