(47, 11, 14, 66, 12, 9, 9, NULL, 'Deception of Satan', 'Both passages emphasize the deceptive nature of Satan. In 2 Corinthians, he is described as transforming into an ''angel of light,'' while in Revelation, he is identified as one who ''deceiveth the whole world.''', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 11, 14, 40, 4, 1, 10, 'Satan himself is transformed into an angel of light', 'Temptation and Deception', 'Both passages emphasize the deceptive nature of Satan, who presents himself as an angel of light while tempting Jesus. This connection highlights the theme of spiritual warfare and the need for discernment against false appearances.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 11, 14, 1, 3, 1, 5, NULL, 'Deception of Satan', 'This connection highlights the deceptive nature of Satan, who appears as an ''angel of light'' in 2 Corinthians, paralleling the serpent''s subtlety in Genesis. Both passages emphasize the theme of manipulation and the distortion of truth.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 11, 15, 50, 3, 19, 19, 'whose end shall be according to their works', 'End and Destruction Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''end'' related to one''s actions. In 2 Corinthians, the ''end'' is determined by works, while in Philippians, it is linked to destruction, highlighting a contrast in outcomes based on one''s focus.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 11, 15, 66, 9, 11, 11, 'transformed as the ministers of righteousness', 'Transformation of Ministers', 'This connection highlights the theme of transformation, as both passages discuss figures that appear as something they are not. In 2 Corinthians, ministers are transformed as ministers of righteousness, while Revelation describes a king who embodies destruction under the guise of authority.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
