(47, 11, 15, 40, 7, 15, 16, 'ministers of righteousness', 'Connection of False Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the transformation of individuals who appear righteous but are deceptive. The warning in Matthew about false prophets aligns with the idea in 2 Corinthians that ministers can be transformed into ministers of righteousness, indicating a potential for false appearances.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 11, 15, 44, 13, 10, 10, 'ministers of righteousness', 'Connection of Righteousness and Deception', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between righteousness and deceit. In 2 Corinthians, ministers of righteousness are mentioned, while Acts describes an enemy of righteousness who perverts the ways of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 11, 15, 47, 3, 9, 9, 'ministers of righteousness', 'Ministers of Righteousness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of righteousness. The ''ministration of righteousness'' in 2 Corinthians 3:9 relates to the ''ministers of righteousness'' in 2 Corinthians 11:15, highlighting the transformative nature of their roles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 11, 16, 47, 11, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection of Folly in Paul', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of folly, with Paul inviting the Corinthians to bear with him in his foolishness. This connection highlights his use of boasting as a rhetorical device to communicate his message.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(47, 11, 16, 47, 12, 6, 6, 'as a fool receive me', 'Boasting and Foolishness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of boasting and the perception of foolishness. In 2 Corinthians 11:16, Paul acknowledges the potential for being seen as a fool while boasting, and in 2 Corinthians 12:6, he expresses a desire to avoid being perceived as a fool despite his truthfulness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
